items.title: Incorrect behavior of list_projects with multiple filters.

labels.name: api: cloudresourcemanager
labels.description: Issues related to the Resource Manager API.

labels.name: priority: p1
labels.description: Medium priority. Will be fixed prior to next release.

labels.name: type: bug
labels.description: Error or flaw in code with unintended results or allowing sub-optimal usage patterns.

items.body:
#### Environment details

  - OS type and version: `Linux 5.2.17`
  - Python version: `3.7`
  - pip version: `18.1`
  - `google-cloud-resource-manager` version: `0.30.1`

#### Steps to reproduce

  1. Make a list_projects call with multiple filters specified.
  2. The results from server show that only the last filter specified in the input was applied.  Per examples in the [API documentation](https://cloud.google.com/resource-manager/reference/rest/v1beta1/projects/list), the results should only include records that match all filters.

#### Code example

```python
from google.cloud import resource_manager
import sys

def searchProject(label_num):
    labels_filter = {"labels.env": "prod", "labels.type": "red"}
    client = resource_manager.Client()
    print(labels_filter)
    for project in client.list_projects(filter_params=labels_filter):
        print(project)
    # Results include all projects that match the second filter (labels.type=red)
    # First filter (labels.env=prod) is completely disregarded.

searchProject(sys.argv[1])
```

items.title: gcloud auth application-default login vs gcloud auth login

labels.name: api: cloudresourcemanager
labels.description: Issues related to the Resource Manager API.

labels.name: type: docs
labels.description: Improvement to the documentation for an API.

items.body:
Hi! I ran into an issue following the documentation for creating a client.  From the documentation:

> This means that for this API you should always use the credentials provided by the Google Cloud SDK, which you can get by running gcloud auth login.
> 
> Once you run that command, google-cloud-python will automatically pick up the credentials, and you can use the "automatic discovery" feature of the library.

Following those instructions to create a client results in the following error (even though `gcloud auth login` was successful):

```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "test.py", line 2, in <module>
    client = resource_manager.Client()
  File "/Users/jnalley/.virtualenv/lib/python3.8/site-packages/google/cloud/resource_manager/client.py", line 72, in __init__
    super(Client, self).__init__(credentials=credentials, _http=_http)
  File "/Users/jnalley/.virtualenv/lib/python3.8/site-packages/google/cloud/client.py", line 132, in __init__
    credentials, _ = google.auth.default()
  File "/Users/jnalley/.virtualenv/lib/python3.8/site-packages/google/auth/_default.py", line 321, in default
    raise exceptions.DefaultCredentialsError(_HELP_MESSAGE)
google.auth.exceptions.DefaultCredentialsError: Could not automatically determine credentials. Please set GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS or explicitly create credentials and re-run the application. For more information, please see https://cloud.google.com/docs/authentication/getting-started
```

I found an entry on [stackoverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/48088841/gcloud-auth-login-saves-to-legacy-credentials-folder) that suggested passing `application-default` when running `gcloud auth`.

Using the command `gcloud auth application-default login` instead of `gcloud auth login` allows me to instantiate the client (although a warning is still displayed indicating that the application authenticated using `user` credentials instead of a service account).

Should the documentation be [updated](https://github.com/jnalley/python-resource-manager/commit/4a59d2a4c95049b8050c1a250838761fc59ea136) to reflect this difference or am I doing something wrong.  Thanks!

items.title: create() returns 403 or 400

labels.name: api: cloudresourcemanager
labels.description: Issues related to the Resource Manager API.

labels.name: type: question
labels.description: Request for information or clarification. Not an issue.

items.body:
Hi.

With shutdown of Fabric, Google Analytics for Apps and Google Cloud Messaging, it has become critical for external entities to programmatically create new Google Cloud Projects to programmatically create new Firebase projects.

There is no other interface/API for us to do this. Google's purchases, mergers and deprecations/shutdowns have forced us into a position where we cannot manage crash reporting, push notifications or analytics without creating a Google Cloud Project, and we cannot programmatically create a Google Cloud Project, nor can we programmatically access Firebase's push notification token (yes, I know that's not part of this issue. It's just more fuel for my ire).

403 is returned using version 1beta1. [400 is returned using version 1 because the create method does not accept arguments](https://cloudresourcemanager.googleapis.com/$discovery/rest?version=v1). [Version 2 has no project management resources](https://cloudresourcemanager.googleapis.com/$discovery/rest?version=v2).

My queries

1) Does anyone at Google care about this?
2) Is enabling create() actually on a backlog?
3) Do you know when this feature will be delivered?

My preferred option would be to remove the Google Corporate filtering on the beta API, because the documentation for the resource manager strongly implies that create() is available to all public users!
